{"type":"assistant","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"- Assumptions\nThe core assumption is that a feature exists to be designed, yet the problem space, use cases, and actors have been entirely omitted from the prompt. We assume nothing about data shape, volume, consistency, network availability, or user intent because no foundational facts have been provided. The starting point is absolute zero.\n\n- Failure Modes\nAttempting to design a data model without explicit constraints guarantees an incorrect abstraction that will require complete replacement. Trust boundaries cannot be drawn without explicitly identifying the system's actors and external interfaces. Guessing boundaries introduces critical security vulnerabilities by default.\n\n- Fallbacks\nThe system must halt architecture design until the required inputs are supplied. We cannot rely on industry standards or common patterns as stand-ins for actual requirements, as those are assumptions posing as facts.\n\n- Foundation\nThe bedrock cannot be laid on zero data. No types, interfaces, schemas, or security models can be proposed until the core atomic components of the feature are explicitly named and verified. \n\n- Verification Flags\nThe next verification step requires explicit input. To proceed, provide the missing evidence:\n1. **The Feature Specification**: What is the core state being managed or transformed?\n2. **The Actors**: Who or what interacts with this system?\n3. **The Interfaces**: What external boundaries or network constraints exist? dependencies**: What external systems or networks does this feature touch?"}]},"session_id":"0b97cdad-a18d-4a49-acd2-03018da71553"}
